{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522312"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:43:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:43:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13820"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13820"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.14,0.02,0.74,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6437"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55834"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6437","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6437"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13820"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41380"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"237"},{"type":"tags","id":"1367"},{"type":"tags","id":"2093"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12714"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12715"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31079"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55834"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents to the surgical clinic with non-healing ulcers on both lower legs. She has no significant medical or surgical history and takes no regular medications. She works as a theatre nurse. She denies smoking or excessive alcohol intake. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The appearance of the leg ulcers is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis for this patient\u0027s presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arterial ulcers","Pyoderma gangrenosum","Pressure ulcers","Venous ulcers","Squamous cell carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image and clinical presentation are most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Evenous ulcers\u003C/strong\u003E. Venous ulcers are the most common type of leg ulcers, typically occurring on the medial aspect of the lower leg. They are characterised by shallow, irregularly shaped ulcers with associated skin changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKey features of venous ulcers visible in this case include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E- Shallow ulceration\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E- Haemosiderin deposits (brownish discolouration of the surrounding skin)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E- Lipodermatosclerosis (hardening and tightening of the skin)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E- Location on the lower leg (medial, Gaiter area)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArterial ulcers\u003C/strong\u003E are typically more painful, have a \u0027punched out\u0027 appearance, and are often located on the toes, heels, or bony prominences of the foot. They are usually associated with poor peripheral pulses and a history of claudication, which are not mentioned in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPyoderma gangrenosum\u003C/strong\u003E is an inflammatory condition that causes painful, rapidly progressing ulcers. These ulcers often have a violaceous border and can occur anywhere on the body, not just the legs. They are also typically associated with systemic diseases such as inflammatory bowel disease or rheumatoid arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPressure ulcers\u003C/strong\u003E occur over bony prominences in patients with limited mobility. They are unlikely in this ambulatory patient who works as a theatre nurse.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESquamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E can present as a non-healing ulcer, but it typically has raised, rolled edges and a history of rapid growth. It is also usually solitary rather than bilateral.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s occupation as a theatre nurse, which involves prolonged standing, may contribute to venous insufficiency and ulcer formation. Management of venous ulcers typically involves:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECompression therapy: This is the cornerstone of treatment, usually with multi-layer compression bandaging or compression stockings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWound care: Regular cleaning and dressing of the wound, often with non-adherent dressings to maintain a moist wound environment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EElevation of the legs: Encouraging the patient to elevate their legs when resting to reduce oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAddressing underlying venous insufficiency: This may involve lifestyle modifications (e.g., weight loss, exercise) or interventional procedures such as endovenous ablation or sclerotherapy for varicose veins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPain management: As needed, usually with simple analgesics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENutritional support: Ensuring adequate nutrition to support wound healing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESkin care: Moisturising the surrounding skin to prevent further breakdown.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EReferral to a vascular specialist may be warranted for further evaluation and management, especially if the ulcers are large, longstanding, or not responding to initial treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Venous ulcers typically occur on the medial aspect of the lower leg, often with associated skin changes such as lipodermatosclerosis and haemosiderin deposits.","Venous ulcers are usually shallow, irregularly shaped, and may be associated with varicose veins or a history of deep vein thrombosis.","Differential diagnosis of leg ulcers includes arterial ulcers, pyoderma gangrenosum, pressure ulcers, and malignancies such as squamous cell carcinoma."],"references":["Robles-Tenorio A, Lev-Tov H, Ocampo-Candiani J. Venous Leg Ulcer. In: StatPearls [Online]. [Updated 2022 Sep 18]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK567802/","Oakley A. Differential diagnosis of leg ulcer. In: Dermnet [online]. 2016. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/differential-diagnosis-of-leg-ulcer"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41380"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13820"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20767"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20767","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20767"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/B9ZlV5s1hLlOR21i0NT1DZd6sjBh3h.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/B9ZlV5s1hLlOR21i0NT1DZd6sjBh3h.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":768,"height":1024}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41380"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-18T11:51:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-18T11:52:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6437"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55834"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1